text.text: A Guide to Walthamstow

Allow the Victoria Line to carry you to its terminus and you find yourself in a far Northeastern corner of London. Walthamstow boasts an intriguing combination of the rural (The Village) and the urban (High Street). The result is a diverse and tight-knit community buzzing with exciting local projects and independent businesses.
Best for... local lessons and community coffees

tip.text:
Spend enough time in The Hornbeam and you might just purge yourself of all the ailments of modern life - the place is solar powered for Christ’s sake. These good people are all about community, local produce, and keeping you green as a grasshopper. The seasonal menu (spelled out in fridge magnets) is primarily vegan and always tasty - come in the week for something simple like their pumpkin and kale tart, or on the weekend for their full English brekkie.

Food aside, the music is straight-up soulful and they even host classes. Pop in for a Jamming class (jam making) or a Jammin’ class (guitar skills). Or both. Heck, we’re community converts.

text.html: The Hornbeam is the organic, beating heart of Walthamstow. It does not get more grassroots than this: growing projects, eco-friendly refills of household cleaning liquids, whole Mondays of classes led by locals and a monthly seasonal supper club.
text.text: The Hornbeam is the organic, beating heart of Walthamstow. It does not get more grassroots than this: growing projects, eco-friendly refills of household cleaning liquids, whole Mondays of classes led by locals and a monthly seasonal supper club.
Best for... cosy cafe culture

tip.text:
This cosy, family-run cafe is a proper gem. Sisters Stella and Tiggy returned from their travels in America with a dream: this is it. Their mum Anna has been baking like crazy for over a year now and you can expect a serious Greek influence in her delights - keep your eyes peeled for her signature Spinach & Feta Pie, laced with dill for good measure. And did someone say Greek-style BBQs in the summer?

Wynwood also display and sell the work of local creatives for no commission and the mural out back comes courtesy of Wood Street Walls. Hopes for the coming year include more events, pop up restaurants and an alcohol license. Sounds good to us.

text.html: Looking to camp up in a cafe for the day? You’ll be greeted here with a friendly smile, the coffee is top notch, the owners’ mum whips up delightful baked goods and the walls showcase the best local art. It’s cosy as hell. Plus the boards out front always carry a philosophical one-liner if you’re after some food for thought.

Best for... sensory stimulation

tip.text:
This neontopia will have you doing double, wait triple, no - quadruple takes. Sensory overload. The Braceys have been making neon since 1952. This wonderland of props includes a luminous, gun toting Jesus and a Statue of Liberty with ‘I’m waiting for my man’ emblazoned in bright pink across her torso. You can even sit and take it all in over some cake and a coffee.

Enter John Blake, curator. Any individual keen to stress both names and a title is likely a character, and this eccentric and charming gentleman tops the lot. Illustrator and lover of Japan, the man fits right in amongst the kaleidoscopic chaos and cited the sign from Kubrick’s ‘Eyes Wide Shut’ as one of his personal favourites.

text.text: Probably the last thing you’d expect to stumble across on an industrial complex in far North East London. Yes, God’s Own Junkyard is every bit as bizarre as the name suggests. This eclectic array of neon signs and obscure movie props will invariably prove an eye-opening experience for anyone. We’re still having flashbacks.
Best for... pie & mash

tip.text:
Step into Walthamstow’s very own time portal. The year is 1927 and the order is either jellied eel or pie & mash. Other than a couple of tabletops and the mighty lurch into the modern era, from gas to electric power, nothing in this spot has changed. That means the same menu, the same recipes, served up in the same sacred dishes. With tiled walls, gas heaters and retro booths L. Manze boasts one of the more intriguing menus we’ve ever seen. Is the carton of liquor on offer a boozy juicebox? Go find out.

From the outside, this nationally listed building is a real sight to behold - the original exterior remains, wooden door and window frames in all their glory. An authentic and legendary East end eatery if ever there was one.

text.text: Once upon a time jellied eel was all the rage. That time may well be behind us now, but L. Manze has lasted and earned its reputation as a timeless East End institution. Grab a booth, tuck into a pie and marvel at the unchanged interior. This one’s a real journey into the city’s slippery history.
Best for... a pint with the locals

tip.text:
On the comically named Hoe Street (nah we refuse to mature), sits this all-singing, all-dancing theatre pub. Ye Old Rose and Crown provides a pretty reasonable line up of events, including DJs, gigs, open mic nights, comedy, plays and even the odd panto. Yep there's always something going on.

It's a historic place, full of locals - the kind of pub that really smells of pub with patterned carpets and bountiful ales. Open till 1am on Fridays and Saturdays it's a safe bet for that late drink you think you can't live without.

Check their socials for food pop ups and Sunday roast plans, there might just be something, there might not.

text.text: If we hadn’t popped into the locals’ favourite boozer then we’d have to retract all claims about having it large. Don’t fret though because that isn’t the case. This theatre pub is the best place for a pint and play - may as well go for the hat-trick. Also please appreciate how many beermats they’ve got on the walls.
Best for... getting your dine on

tip.text:
From the people who brought us Bacon Jam comes Walthamstow's very own Eat 17. The mission statement is simple: proper British food - ethically sourced, expertly prepared, fairly priced. The bread is made onsite and all the meat comes from The East London Sausage Company across the road. Local enough for you? We thought so.

We like the sound of the 7 hour braised lamb shoulder, joined on its plate by crispy sweetbread and garlic parmesan pomme puree. Don't let us make that decision for you though, go and investigate yourself - we're sure you won't be left disappointed. They also own the independent convenience store and deli next door, so be sure to pop in.

text.text: Basically, the people of Walthamstow care deeply about promoting local businesses. Eat 17 ain’t letting the team down - British food of the highest quality, produce sourced from guess where? Yep, this delightful corner of the world. They’ve also added ‘Chorizo Jam’ to their repertoire, as if the bacon one wasn’t genius enough.
Best for... coffee & cocktails in a pineapple paradise

tip.text:
Warren set up shop in this old accountants firm 2 years ago and damn does the space look fly. Industrial style free-hanging lights and a 30 year back catalogue of National Geographic. Notice the pineapple theme running throughout, from the gorgeous mural on the side of the building to the original Andrew McGregor prints on the walls. Expect proper coffee, toasties and salads all week and full brunch on weekends. Peep the 56 Pineapple Special Toastie - spiced pineapple chutney and extra mature cheddar on E5 sourdough. Yes.

56 St James are looking to ramp up the cocktail game from here on out (already open for ‘em on Friday evenings). Expect this to extend to Thursdays and Saturdays - watch this space keenly.

text.text: Does your favourite coffee shop ever moonlight as your favourite cocktail bar? No, us neither. The lucky people of Walthamstow however are fortunate enough to have this spot knocking about. Kick back with your choice of poison and count all the pineapple references or, better yet, flick through a vintage edition of National Geographic.
Best for...sourdough pies straight out the oven

tip.text:
Sodo (short for sourdough) is everything this pizza café is based on, and we love them for it. They ferment their dough for up to 48 hours (we’re already impressed), make use of fresh ingredients from local growing communities (swoon) and serve a selection of local ales.

The Sodo crew’s dedication to serving proper pizza to the masses couldn’t be clearer. The menu is made of four classics: cured meats, margheritas, goats cheese and butternut squash but today we’re here for the daily special - tomato, mozzarella, parma ham and rocket. We’d also recommend asking them to plonk a serving of burratina on top (available from the starter menu).

text.text: Sodo is a straightforward and tasty operation, as every good pizzeria should be. They ferment their dough for up to 48 hours before putting on fresh and simple ingredients to create a short menu full of truly delicious pies. It's a casual, relaxed and inexpensive experience and, to be frank that's all we're asking for.
Best for...an arts hub with grandeur

tip.text:
It's always refreshing to see a venue that's taken on something laid to waste and moulded it into something new whilst retaining that faded grandeur. Mirth, Marvel & Maud is one such gem. In a Grade-II listed old cinema that Hitchcock used to come to, it's been converted into a community hub, bar and arts space.

Amongst the grand chandeliers, William Morris-inspired decor, ornate mirrors and grand sweeping central staircase, it's a real nice setting for a drink. Mirth is the foyer bar and restaurant; Maud the screening room and arts space that hosts gigs, films and general performance-y related bits and pieces.

text.text:

Best for... live music and a barrel of crafts

tip.text:
Wildcard have been at their alchemy in this spot for a couple of years now but they’ve come from the humblest of beginnings. Two guys met working in Boots before going off to university where they tried their hand at brewing, from bedrooms to bathtubs. Now though they're properly legit and whipping up some magical flavours, open to us muggles Friday through Sunday. We strongly recommend you dip your beak in their Black IPA.

Thurston Moore of Sonic Youth has played here before and is looking to do more shows in the near future. Wildcard’s William tells us that the plan moving ahead is to throw more gigs, maybe build a small platform and get more of their crafty kegs around town.

text.text: Meanwhile, more reasons to make the trip to a very unspectacular looking industrial complex. Grab a goblet of gorgeous beer at the Wildcard Brewery and have a chat with the friendly chaps masterminding the operation. The beer really is delightful. Did we say that already?
Best for... hand-picked, homemade ginfusions

address.line1: Unit 18, Ravenswood Industrial Estate, Shernhall Street

tip.text:
Set in an old munitions factory, tucked away on an industrial estate in Walthamstow comes Mother’s Ruin. Becky started out with a small shop on Wood Street Market selling fruit liqueurs, and has moved on to bigger and better things: her very own Gin Palace. She grows around half of the fruit herself, including the sloes she picks in Essex. Once picked, the fruits are added to a spirit base and left to sit for a year.

Swing by and pick up some fruity gin in a lovely stone glazed bottle or treat yourself to a Damsun in Distress, her signature cocktail. Other reasons to pop in include a monthly curry night and a bingo evening (gin-go). Expect more food pop ups to come.

text.text: Stumble across the plot from Wildcard and discover the wonders of Mother’s Ruin. Gin with a fruity twist, delightful cocktails and, since over half the fruit is homegrown, well in keeping with Walthamstow’s community ethos. We hear the Ravenswood Industrial Estate is the place to be on a summer’s day - neon, beer & gin a plenty - so we’ll be seeing you there.
Best for...Chinese like you've never had it

tip.text:
This isn't your normal Chinese restaurant. There’s no MSG or sweet & sour chicken to be found here, oh no - instead, this place focuses on Uyghur dishes, from the Muslim ethnic group found in western-most China. The cuisine is a curious concoction of Chinese, Middle Eastern & Persian influences, and the menu features typical Uyghur dishes such as ‘Ganbian Chaomian’ and 'Ququre'. There are also some more daring dishes like marinated cow's stomach, which we've heard is delish, if you can stomach it...

The insides are decorated with wall hangings, doppa hats and miniature musical instruments, which adds to its curious ambience. It’s also a family run business, and there’s some serious convivial vibes making you feel nice and homely. Heads up, it's a Halal restaurant so don't expect any pork or alcohol - but what they lack here, we can assure they make up elsewhere.

text.text: This is far from your usual Chinese. There's no MSG or sweet & sour chicken to be found here, oh no - instead, this place focuses on Uyghur dishes, a curious concoction of Chinese, Middle Eastern & Persian influences. Whatever it is, it's hella tasty. With wall hangings, doppa hats and musical instruments filling the space, this is a convivial and homely place to get good and full.
